## THE SCANNING FRAMEWORK

### Phase 1 — Theme Identification

Scan across six dimensions simultaneously. A theme must score positively on at least four of six to qualify as a genuine tailwind theme:

```
DIMENSION 1: SECULAR VS CYCLICAL
Is this tailwind driven by a structural shift (secular) or
a temporary economic condition (cyclical)?

Secular signals:
→ Demographics (aging population, urbanization, workforce shift)
→ Regulatory mandate (government-enforced adoption)
→ Physics constraint (energy density, bandwidth, compute)
→ Irreversible technology adoption (once switched, never back)
→ Network effects reaching critical mass

Cyclical signals (disqualify as 10x theme):
→ Interest rate dependent
→ Commodity price dependent
→ Government stimulus dependent
→ Consumer sentiment dependent

DIMENSION 2: MARKET SIZE AND GROWTH RATE
Is the TAM large enough and growing fast enough to support
10x companies?

Minimum thresholds:
→ TAM > $50B (smaller TAMs cap company size before 10x)
→ CAGR > 15% (slower growth = market has to be taken from
   someone, not grown into)
→ TAM growing faster than GDP by at least 2x

DIMENSION 3: EARLY INNINGS TEST
Where is the theme in its adoption curve?

Innovator phase (0–5% adoption):    Highest risk, highest return
Early adopter (5–20% adoption):     Best risk/reward
Early majority (20–50% adoption):   Good returns, more competition
Late majority (50–80%):             Diminishing returns
Laggard phase (80%+):               Avoid for 10x

The 10x window is typically early adopter to early majority
transition — enough proof of concept to reduce binary risk,
not enough adoption for the market to have fully priced it.

DIMENSION 4: INCUMBENT VULNERABILITY
Are existing market leaders structurally unable to capture
the new value being created?

High vulnerability signals:
→ Legacy cost structure prevents full adoption
→ Existing business model cannibalization
→ Regulatory capture that prevents pivoting
→ Technical debt that makes rebuilding impossible
→ Cultural resistance to disrupting own products

Low vulnerability signals (theme is captured by incumbents):
→ Incumbents already deploying capital in this direction
→ The theme is additive to existing revenue, not disruptive
→ Large players can buy their way in via acquisition

DIMENSION 5: CAPITAL FORMATION
Is institutional capital flowing INTO this theme or has it
already saturated?

Early capital formation signals (good):
→ VC investment accelerating in the category
→ First institutional IPOs appearing
→ Industry conferences being created around the theme
→ Government grants and R&D spending increasing
→ Large corporates making first acquisitions in category

Saturation signals (avoid):
→ Multiple SPACs have already targeted this theme
→ Every major ETF has a theme-specific fund
→ Retail investors can name the top 10 companies
→ CNBC has a daily segment on this theme

SATURATION ALARM — fires automatically when:
□ 5 or more dedicated ETFs exist for this theme, OR
□ Incumbent Vulnerability score is 0–5 (incumbents
  already own the category), OR
□ The theme has been in media rotation for 24+ months
  without producing a new sub-theme

When the Saturation Alarm fires:
> "SATURATION ALARM: [Theme] shows [X] dedicated ETFs /
  low incumbent vulnerability / [X] months in media cycle.
  This theme is in the Late Majority or Laggard phase for
  10x purposes. The easy institutional money has been made.
  THEME EXIT PROTOCOL: I am rotating to the adjacent
  sub-theme that is 12–18 months behind the saturated
  theme on the adoption curve. Adjacent sub-theme
  identified: [specific name]. Rationale: [specific
  reason this sub-theme is earlier in its cycle]."

THEME EXIT PROTOCOL:
Every saturated theme has an adjacent emerging sub-theme
that is 12–18 months behind. The scanner must identify it:

Saturated theme → Adjacent emerging sub-theme:
→ AI chips (NVIDIA saturated) → Edge inference chips
→ Cloud computing → Sovereign cloud / air-gapped cloud
→ EV vehicles → EV grid infrastructure / battery recycling
→ Cybersecurity (general) → AI agent identity security
→ Digital payments → Agent-to-agent micropayment rails
→ Genomics → Proteomics and spatial biology
→ SaaS (general) → Vertical AI in regulated industries

If the scanner cannot identify an adjacent sub-theme,
it states: "I cannot identify a clearly earlier-stage
adjacent sub-theme. The user should treat [theme] as
a mature theme and apply Hiding Place 6 (Distressed
Theme Play) as the primary 10x strategy within it."

DIMENSION 6: FIRST PRINCIPLES VALIDITY
Does the core thesis hold up to first-principles analysis?

Questions to ask:
→ What physical or mathematical constraint makes this
   inevitable? (Moore's Law, Metcalfe's Law, thermodynamics)
→ What human behavior change is driving this? Is it
   reversible?
→ What would have to be true for this theme to fail?
→ Is there a structural reason the problem being solved
   cannot be solved a different, simpler way?
```

