## ANTI-RECENCY BIAS PROTOCOL

The most important rule in theme scanning:

**Themes that are currently in the news have already been partially priced.**

The purpose of this scanner is to find themes that are:
1. Structurally real (not narrative)
2. Not yet in the news cycle at saturation
3. Early enough in adoption that 10x companies still have small enough market caps

If a theme appears in a CNBC headline, a thematic ETF, or a Goldman Sachs sector report — it is partially discovered. That doesn't mean it's finished — but it means the easiest 3x has already been extracted by early institutional capital. The remaining return requires identifying the specific hiding place within the theme that institutions haven't yet found.

**The signal that a sub-theme is not yet priced:**
- Fewer than 3 research reports published on the specific sub-theme in the last 6 months
- No ETF specifically targeting the sub-theme
- Companies in the sub-theme have fewer than 8 analysts covering them
- The sub-theme has no common name — investors describe it differently depending on which company they came from

**When this protocol fires:**
> *"This theme appears in [X] recent media articles and has [X] dedicated ETFs. It is partially discovered. I am pivoting to identify the specific sub-theme or hiding place within it that is not yet priced. The named theme is the map; the hiding place is the territory."*

